      "review_text": "I wanted to share my experience at Sparsh Hospital, Yeshwanthpur, which has been deeply traumatic for me and my family.\n\nIn April 2022, I had a C-section at this hospital, and unfortunately, the entire process was filled with stress, confusion, and a lack of compassionate care.\n\nI was called in for a routine check-up just a few days after my previous one, only to be suddenly asked to get admitted. With little time to prepare, we rushed home to pick up a few essentials and returned to the hospital. Later that evening, I was taken to the labor room, where a doctor was asked to break my amniotic sac. The pain was unbearable, and I immediately felt that something was not right. Shortly after, I was told there was a complication and was rushed for an emergency C-section.\n\nDuring the surgery, I was conscious and could hear everything. To make things even worse, the doctor who had broken my amniotic sac felt giddy and left the OT to rest, an incident my family witnessed, adding to their panic.\n\nAfter delivering a healthy baby girl, she was only shown to me from a distance and immediately taken away. My family was not allowed to hold her, and she was kept in the NICU overnight without explanation. The hospital cited breathing issues, but what remains unclear is why skin-to-skin contact was denied, even though it is medically proven to regulate a baby’s temperature, breathing, and heart rate, while also reducing stress for both mother and child.\n\nDespite the fact that I was producing breast milk, my baby was fed formula milk in the NICU, leading to latching issues. The hospital provided no support for breastfeeding, and I had to seek help from a lactation consultant later on.\n\nThis entire experience left us traumatized, to the extent that a family who once wanted two children decided against having more. Even today, not a single day passes without me reliving the trauma—it remains as fresh as the day it happened.\n\nI cannot help but wonder: Was this an unnecessary C-section? Was there an intentional preference for formula over breastfeeding? Or was it simply a lack of care for the well-being of mothers and babies?\n\nI truly hope the hospital re-evaluates its practices to ensure no other mother or family has to go through such an ordeal. Childbirth should be a joyous experience, not one filled with confusion, distress, and unanswered questions.",
